Abdul Qadeer Khan, the Pakistani scientist behind the atomic bomb, supplied highly enriched uranium to Iran in 2001.
This led to concerns about Iran's nuclear ambitions.
A report revealed a scheme to deliver a uranium enrichment plant to Libya, accelerating their nuclear program.
Khan's network also implicated South African figures.
Despite denials, Pakistan faced scrutiny for aiding US efforts in Iran.
Khan's actions raised questions about Pakistan's knowledge of his activities.
The International Atomic Energy Agency investigated Iran's nuclear program, suspecting a weapons agenda.
Khan's proliferation network posed challenges for US intelligence and international cooperation.
